# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: winui
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] Direct3D contains many commands for 3D computer graphics rendering; however, since version 8, Direct3D has superseded the DirectDraw framework and also taken responsibility for the rendering of 2D graphics.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] Microsoft strives to continually update Direct3D to support the latest technology available on 3D graphics cards.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] Direct3D offers full vertex software emulation but no pixel software emulation for features not available in hardware.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] The API does include a *Reference Rasterizer* (or REF device), which emulates a generic graphics card in software, although it is too slow for most real-time 3D applications and is typically only used for debugging.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] A new real-time software rasterizer, *WARP*, designed to emulate the complete feature set of Direct3D 10.1, is included with Windows 7 and Windows Vista Service Pack 2 with the Platform Update; its performance is said to be on par with lower-end 3D cards on multi-core CPUs.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] As part of DirectX, Direct3D is available for Windows 95 and above, and is the base for the vector graphics API on the different versions of Xbox console systems.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] The Wine compatibility layer, a free software reimplementation of several Windows APIs, includes an implementation of Direct3D.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] Direct3D's main competitor is Khronos' OpenGL and its follow-on Vulkan.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] Fahrenheit was an attempt by Microsoft and SGI to unify OpenGL and Direct3D in the 1990s, but was eventually cancelled.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] In 1992, Servan Keondjian, Doug Rabson and Kate Seekings started a company named RenderMorphics, which developed a 3D graphics API named Reality Lab, which was used in medical imaging and CAD software.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] Microsoft bought RenderMorphics in February 1995, bringing its staff on board to implement a 3D graphics engine for Windows 95.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] Direct3D initially implemented an "immediate mode" 3D API and layered upon it a "retained mode" 3D API.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] Both types of API were already offered with the second release of Reality Lab before Direct3D was released.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] Like other DirectX APIs, such as DirectDraw, both were based on COM.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] The retained mode API was a scene graph API that attained little adoption.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] Game developers clamored for more direct control of the hardware's activities than the Direct3D retained mode could provide.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] Only two games that sold a significant volume, *Lego Island* and *Lego Rock Raiders*, were based on the Direct3D retained mode, so Microsoft did not update the retained mode API after DirectX 3.0.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] For DirectX 2.0 and 3.0, the Direct3D immediate mode used an "execute buffer" programming model that Microsoft hoped hardware vendors would support directly.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] Execute buffers were intended to be allocated in hardware memory and parsed by the hardware to perform the 3D rendering.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] They were considered extremely awkward to program at the time, however, hindering adoption of the new API and prompting calls for Microsoft to adopt OpenGL as the official 3D rendering API for games as well as workstation applications.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] Rather than adopt OpenGL as a gaming API, Microsoft chose to continue improving Direct3D, not only to be competitive with OpenGL, but to compete more effectively with other proprietary APIs such as 3dfx's Glide.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] From the beginning, the immediate mode also supported Talisman's tiled rendering with the BeginScene/EndScene methods of the IDirect3DDevice interface.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] No substantive changes were planned to Direct3D for **DirectX 4.0**, which was scheduled to ship in late 1996 and then cancelled.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] In December 1996, a team in Redmond took over development of the Direct3D Immediate Mode, while the London-based RenderMorphics team continued work on the Retained Mode.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] The Redmond team added the DrawPrimitive API that eliminated the need for applications to construct execute buffers, making Direct3D more closely resemble other immediate mode rendering APIs such as Glide and OpenGL.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] The first beta of DrawPrimitive shipped in February 1997, and the final version shipped with **DirectX 5.0** in August 1997.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] Besides introducing an easier-to-use immediate mode API, DirectX 5.0 added the SetRenderTarget method that enabled Direct3D devices to write their graphical output to a variety of DirectDraw surfaces.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] A minor update to **DirectX 6.0** came in the February, 1999 DirectX 6.1 update.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] Besides adding DirectMusic support for the first time, this release improved support for Intel Pentium III 3D extensions.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] A confidential memo sent in 1997 shows Microsoft planning to announce full support for Talisman in DirectX 6.0, but the API ended up being cancelled (See the Microsoft Talisman page for details).
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] Direct3D was not considered to be user friendly, but as of DirectX version 8.1, many usability problems were resolved.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] Direct3D 8 contained many powerful 3D graphics features, such as vertex shaders, pixel shaders, fog, bump mapping and texture mapping.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] Windows Vista includes a major update to the Direct3D API.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] Originally called WGF 2.0 (Windows Graphics Foundation 2.0), then DirectX 10 and DirectX Next, **Direct3D 10** features an updated shader model 4.0 and optional interruptibility for shader programs.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] In this model shaders still consist of fixed stages as in previous versions, but all stages support a nearly unified interface, as well as a unified access paradigm for resources such as textures and shader constants.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] The language itself has been extended to be more expressive, including integer operations, a greatly increased instruction count, and more C-like language constructs.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] Windows XP and earlier are not supported by DirectX 10.0 and above.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] Furthermore, Direct3D 10 dropped support for the retained mode API which had been a part of Direct3D since the beginning, making Windows Vista incompatible with 3D games that had used the retained mode API as their rendering engine.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] Unlike prior versions of the API, Direct3D 10 no longer uses "capability bits" (or "caps") to indicate which features are supported on a given graphics device.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] Instead, it defines a minimum standard of hardware capabilities which must be supported for a display system to be "Direct3D 10 compatible".
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] This is a significant departure, with the goal of streamlining application code by removing capability-checking code and special cases based on the presence or absence of specific capabilities.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] Because Direct3D 10 hardware was comparatively rare after the initial release of Windows Vista and because of the massive install base of non-Direct3D 10 compatible graphics cards, the first Direct3D 10-compatible games still provide Direct3D 9 render paths.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] Examples of such titles are games originally written for Direct3D 9 and ported to Direct3D 10 after their release, such as *Company of Heroes*, or games originally developed for Direct3D 9 with a Direct3D 10 path retrofitted later during their development, such as *Hellgate: London* or *Crysis*.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] The DirectX 10 SDK became available in February 2007.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] Direct3D 10.1 sets a few more image quality standards for graphics vendors, and gives developers more control over image quality.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] Features include finer control over anti-aliasing (both multisampling and supersampling with per sample shading and application control over sample position) and more flexibilities to some of the existing features (cubemap arrays and independent blending modes).
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] Unlike Direct3D 10 which strictly required Direct3D 10-class hardware and driver interfaces, Direct3D 10.1 runtime can run on Direct3D 10.0 hardware using a concept of "feature levels", but new features are supported exclusively by new hardware which expose feature level 10_1.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] The only available Direct3D 10.1 hardware as of June 2008 were the Radeon HD 3000 series and Radeon HD 4000 series from ATI; in 2009, they were joined by Chrome 430/440GT GPUs from S3 Graphics and select lower-end models in GeForce 200 series from Nvidia.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] In 2011, Intel chipsets started supporting Direct3D 10.1 with the introduction of Intel HD Graphics 2000 (GMA HD).
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] The Direct3D 11 runtime is able to run on Direct3D 9 and 10.x-class hardware and drivers using the concept of "feature levels", expanding on the functionality first introduced in Direct3D 10.1 runtime.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] There are three "10 Level 9" profiles which encapsulate various capabilities of popular DirectX 9.0a cards, and Direct3D 10, 10.1, and 11 each have a separate feature level; each upper level is a strict superset of a lower level.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] Tessellation was earlier considered for Direct3D 10, but was later abandoned.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] GPUs such as Radeon R600 feature a tessellation engine that can be used with Direct3D 9/10/10.1 and OpenGL, but it's not compatible with Direct3D 11 (according to Microsoft).
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] Older graphics hardware such as Radeon 8xxx, GeForce 3/4 had support for another form of tesselation (RT patches, N patches) but those technologies never saw substantial use.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] As such, their support was dropped from newer hardware.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] Microsoft has also hinted at other features such as order independent transparency, which was never exposed by the Direct3D API but supported almost transparently by early Direct3D hardware such as Videologic's PowerVR line of chips.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] Other notable features are the addition of two new texture compression algorithms for more efficient packing of high quality and HDR/alpha textures and an increased texture cache.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] First seen in the Release Candidate version, Windows 7 integrates the first released Direct3D 11 support.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] The Platform Update for Windows Vista includes full-featured Direct3D 11 runtime and DXGI 1.1 update, as well as other related components from Windows 7 like WARP, Direct2D, DirectWrite, and WIC.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] WARP has been updated to support feature level 11_1.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] The Platform Update for Windows 7 includes a limited set of features from Direct3D 11.1, though components that depend on WDDM 1.2 – such as feature level 11_1 and its related APIs, or quad buffering for stereoscopic rendering – are not present.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] Direct3D 11.X is a superset of DirectX 11.2 running on the Xbox One.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] It includes some features, such as draw bundles, that were later announced as part of DirectX 12.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] Pipeline state objects (PSOs) have evolved from Direct3D 11, and the new concise pipeline states mean that the process has been simplified.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] DirectX 11 offered flexibility in how its states could be altered, to the detriment of performance.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] Simplifying the process and unifying the pipelines (e.g. pixel shader states) lead to a more streamlined process, significantly reducing the overheads and allowing the graphics card to draw more calls for each frame.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] Root signatures introduce configurations to link command lists to resources required by shaders.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] They define the layout of resources that shaders will use and specify what resources will be bound to the pipeline.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] A graphics command list has both a graphics and compute root signature, while a compute command list will have only a compute root signature.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] These root signatures are completely independent of each other.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] While the root signature lays out the types of data for shaders to use, it does not define or map the actual memory or data.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] Root parameters are one type of entry in a root signature.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] The actual values of the root parameters that are modified at runtime are called root arguments.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] Within Direct3D 11, the commands are sent from the CPU to the GPU one by one, and the GPU works through these commands sequentially.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] This means that commands are bottlenecked by the speed at which the CPU can send these commands in a linear fashion.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] Within DirectX 12 these commands are sent as command lists, containing all the required information within a single package.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] The GPU is then capable of computing and executing this command in one single process, without having to wait on any additional information from the CPU.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] Where previously commands were just taken, used, and then forgotten by the GPU, bundles can be reused.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] This decreases the workload of the GPU and means repeated assets can be used much faster.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] While resource binding is fairly convenient in Direct3D 11 for developers at the moment, its inefficiency means several modern hardware capabilities are being drastically underused.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] When a game engine needed resources in DX11, it had to draw the data from scratch every time, meaning repeat processes and unnecessary uses.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] In Direct3D 12, descriptor heaps and tables mean the most often used resources can be allocated by developers in tables, which the GPU can quickly and easily access.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] This can contribute to better performance than Direct3D 11 on equivalent hardware, but it also entails more work for the developer.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] Dynamic Heaps are also a feature of Direct3D 12.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] Direct3D 12 features explicit multi-adapter support, allowing the explicit control of multiple GPUs (mGPU) configuration systems.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] Such configurations can be built with graphics adapter of the same hardware vendor as well of different hardware vendor together.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] An experimental support of D3D 12 for Windows 7 SP1 has been released by Microsoft in 2019 via a dedicated NuGet package.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] Direct3D is a Microsoft DirectX API subsystem component.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] The aim of Direct3D is to abstract the communication between a graphics application and the graphics hardware drivers.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] It is presented like a thin abstract layer at a level comparable to GDI (see attached diagram).
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] Direct3D contains numerous features that GDI lacks.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] Direct3D is an *Immediate mode* graphics API.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] It provides a low-level interface to every video card 3D function (*transformations, clipping, lighting*, *materials*, *textures*, *depth buffering* and so on).
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] It once had a higher level *Retained mode* component, now officially discontinued.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] Direct3D immediate mode presents three main abstractions: *devices*, *resources* and *Swap Chains* (see attached diagram).
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] *Devices* are responsible for rendering the 3D scene.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] They provide an interface with different rendering capabilities.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] For example, the mono device provides white and black rendering, while the RGB device renders in color.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] Every device contains at least one *swap chain*.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] A *swap chain* is made up of one or more back buffer surfaces.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] Moreover, devices contain a collection of *resources*; specific data used during rendering.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] The Microsoft Direct3D 11 API defines a process to convert a group of vertices, textures, buffers, and state into an image on the screen.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] This process is described as a rendering pipeline with several distinct stages.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] **Vertex Shader**: Performs operations on a single vertex at a time, such as transformations, skinning, or lighting.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] **Hull-Shader**: Performs operations on sets of patch control points, and generates additional data known as patch constants.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] **Tessellator**: Subdivides geometry to create higher-order representations of the hull.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] **Domain-Shader**: Performs operations on vertices output by the tessellation stage, in much the same way as a vertex shader.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] **Geometry Shader**: Processes entire primitives such as triangles, points, or lines.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] Given a primitive, this stage discards it, or generates one or more new primitives.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] **Stream-Output**: Can write out the previous stage's results to memory.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] This is useful to recirculate data back into the pipeline.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] **Rasterizer**: Converts primitives into pixels, feeding these pixels into the pixel shader.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] The Rasterizer may also perform other tasks such as clipping what is not visible, or interpolating vertex data into per-pixel data.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] **Pixel Shader**: Determines the final pixel color to be written to the render target and can also calculate a depth value to be written to the depth buffer.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] **Output-Merger**: Merges various types of output data (pixel shader values, alpha blending, depth/stencil...) to build the final result.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] The pipeline stages illustrated with a round box are fully programmable.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] The application provides a shader program that describes the exact operations to be completed for that stage.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] Many stages are optional and can be disabled altogether.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] In Direct3D 5 to 9, when new versions of the API introduced support for new hardware capabilities, most of them were optional – each graphics vendor maintained their own set of supported features in addition to the basic required functionality.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] Support for individual features had to be determined using "capability bits" or "caps", making cross-vendor graphics programming a complex task.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] Direct3D 10 introduced a much simplified set of mandatory hardware requirements based on most popular Direct3D 9 capabilities which all supporting graphics cards had to adhere to, with only a few optional capabilities for supported texture formats and operations.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] Direct3D 10.1 added a few new mandatory hardware requirements, and to remain compatible with 10.0 hardware and drivers, these features were encapsulated in two sets called "feature levels", with 10.1 level forming a superset of 10.0 level.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] As Direct3D 11.0, 11.1 and 12 added support for new hardware, new mandatory capabilities were further grouped in upper feature levels.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] Direct3D 11 also introduced "10level9", a subset of the Direct3D 10 API with three feature levels encapsulating various Direct3D 9 cards with WDDM drivers, and Direct3D 11.1 re-introduced a few optional features for all levels, which were expanded in Direct3D 11.2 and later versions.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] This approach allows developers to unify the rendering pipeline and use a single version of the API on both newer and older hardware, taking advantage of performance and usability improvements in the newer runtime.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] Each upper level is a strict superset of a lower level, with only a few new or previously optional features that move to the core functionality on an upper level.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] More advanced features in a major revision of the Direct3D API such as new shader models and rendering stages are only exposed on up-level hardware.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] Separate capabilities exist to indicate support for specific texture operations and resource formats; these are specified per each texture format using a combination of capability flags.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] Feature levels use underscore as a delimiter (i.e.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] "12_1"), while API/runtime versions use dot (i.e.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] Direct3D 12 for Windows 10 requires graphics hardware conforming to feature levels 11_0 and 11_1 which support virtual memory address translations and requires WDDM 2.0 drivers.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] There are two new feature levels, 12_0 and 12_1, which include some new features exposed by Direct3D 12 that are optional on levels 11_0 and 11_1.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] Some previously optional features are realigned as baseline on levels 11_0 and 11_1.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] Shader Model 6.0 has been released with Windows 10 Creators Update and requires Windows 10 Anniversary Update, WDDM 2.1 drivers.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] Direct3D 12 introduces a revamped resource binding model which allows explicit control of memory.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] Abstract "resource view" objects are now represented with resource descriptors, which are allocated using memory heaps and tables.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] Resource Binding tiers define maximum number of resources that can be addressed using CBV (constant buffer view), SRV (shader resource view) and UAV (unordered access view), as well as texture sampler units.
[src:winui/direct3d-p01] Tier 3 hardware allows fully bindless resources only restricted by the size of the descriptor heap, while Tier 1 and Tier 2 hardware impose some limits on the number of descriptors ("views") that can be used simultaneously.
[src:winui/direct3d-p02] WDDM driver model in Windows Vista and higher supports arbitrarily large number of execution contexts (or threads) in hardware or in software.
[src:winui/direct3d-p02] Windows XP only supported multitasked access to Direct3D, where separate applications could execute in different windows and be hardware accelerated, and the OS had limited control about what the GPU could do and the driver could switch execution threads arbitrarily.
[src:winui/direct3d-p02] The ability to execute the runtime in a multi-threaded mode has been introduced with Direct3D 11 runtime.
[src:winui/direct3d-p02] Each execution context is presented with a resource view of the GPU.
[src:winui/direct3d-p02] Execution contexts are protected from each other, however a rogue or badly written app can take control of the execution in the user-mode driver and could potentially access data from another process within GPU memory by sending modified commands.
[src:winui/direct3d-p02] Though protected from access by another app, a well-written app still needs to protect itself against failures and device loss caused by other applications.
[src:winui/direct3d-p02] The OS manages the threads all by itself, allowing the hardware to switch from one thread to the other when appropriate, and also handles memory management and paging (to system memory and to disk) via integrated OS-kernel memory management.
[src:winui/direct3d-p02] Finer-grained context switching, i.e. being able to switch two execution threads at the shader-instruction level instead of the single-command level or even batch of commands, was introduced in WDDM/DXGI 1.2 which shipped with Windows 8.
[src:winui/direct3d-p02] This overcomes a potential scheduling problem when application would have very long execution of a single command/batch of commands and will have to be terminated by the OS watchdog timer.
[src:winui/direct3d-p02] WDDM 2.0 and DirectX 12 have been reengineered to allow fully multithreaded draw calls.
[src:winui/direct3d-p02] This was achieved by making all resources immutable (i.e. read-only), serializing the rendering states and using draw call bundles.
[src:winui/direct3d-p02] This avoids complex resource management in the kernel-mode driver, making possible multiple reentrant calls to the user-mode driver via concurrent executions contexts supplied by separate rendering threads in the same application.
[src:winui/direct3d-p02] Direct3D Mobile is derived from Direct3D but has a smaller memory footprint.
[src:winui/direct3d-p02] Windows CE provides Direct3D Mobile support.
[src:winui/direct3d-p02] The following alternative implementations of Direct3D API exist.
[src:winui/direct3d-p02] There are several functions that provide complex operations over 3D meshes like tangent-space computation, mesh simplification, precomputed radiance transfer, optimizing for vertex cache friendliness and stripification, and generators for 3D text meshes.
[src:winui/direct3d-p02] 2D features include classes for drawing screen-space lines, text and sprite based particle systems.
[src:winui/direct3d-p02] Spatial functions include various intersection routines, conversion from/to barycentric coordinates and bounding box/sphere generators.
[src:winui/direct3d-p02] D3DX is provided as a dynamic link library (DLL).
[src:winui/direct3d-p02] D3DX is deprecated from Windows 8 onward and can't be used in Windows Store apps.
[src:winui/direct3d-p02] DXUT (also called the sample framework) is a layer built on top of the Direct3D API.
[src:winui/direct3d-p02] The framework is designed to help the programmer spend less time with mundane tasks, such as creating a window, creating a device, processing Windows messages and handling device events.
[src:winui/direct3d-p02] DXUT have been removed with the Windows SDK 8.0 and now distributed as source via CodePlex.
[src:winui/material-design] The purpose of developing Material Design was to create a novel visual language, synthesizing the classic principles of good design with the innovation and potential of technology and science.
[src:winui/material-design] Head designer Matías Duarte explained that "unlike real paper, our digital material expands and reforms intelligently.
[src:winui/material-design] Material has physical surfaces and edges.
[src:winui/material-design] Seams and shadows provide meaning about what you can touch." Material Design is based on paper-and-ink and skeuomorphic interaction concepts, but its implementation is more advanced.
[src:winui/material-design] In 2021, Google revamped the design language, with the new language being titled Material You (Material Design 3).
[src:winui/material-design] It provides more flexibility for designers to create custom themes with varying geometry, colors, and typography.
[src:winui/material-design] In 2025, the next evolution of the design language, titled "Material 3 Expressive", was unveiled.
[src:winui/material-design] Material Design has been gradually rolled out across Google's web and mobile products, providing a consistent experience across all platforms and applications.
[src:winui/material-design] Google has also released application programming interfaces (APIs) for third-party developers to incorporate the design language into their applications.
[src:winui/material-design] The canonical open source implementation of Material Design for web application user interfaces is called Material Web.
[src:winui/material-design] However, there are other official ways to do so, such as, for example, using Flutter or Jetpack Compose.
[src:winui/material-design] After the 2018 revamp, Google began redesigning most of their apps based on an updated set of principles and guidelines dubbed "Material Design 2", which appeared on Android Pie.
[src:winui/material-design] It provided a larger focus on customization of the basic Material Design components to adapt to the branding of the products in which it is being used.
[src:winui/material-design] The updated guidelines further heavily emphasize white space, rounded corners, colorful icons, and bottom navigation bars.
[src:winui/material-design] Google began utilizing a special size-optimized version of their proprietary Product Sans font called Google Sans.
[src:winui/material-design] At Google I/O in May 2021, Google announced a new concept on Android 12 known as "Material You" (also known as "Material Design 3"), emphasizing increased animation, larger buttons, and the ability for custom UI themes to be generated from the user's wallpaper.
[src:winui/material-design] Material You was gradually rolled out to various Google apps on older Android versions in the following months, and acted as a major focus on the Pixel 6 and Pixel 6 Pro smartphone series.
[src:winui/material-design] At The Android Show: I/O Edition in May 2025, Google announced "Material 3 Expressive" for Android 16 and Wear OS 6.
[src:winui/material-design] This version of Material Design shares similarities with its predecessor, and includes improved animations and a more colorful and fun design.
[src:winui/material-design] It was gradually rolled out to Pixel phones (Pixel 6 and newer) and the Pixel Tablet, beginning in September 2025.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] The **Microsoft Store** (formerly known as the **Windows Store**) is a digital distribution platform operated by Microsoft.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] It was created as an app store for Windows 8 as the primary means of distributing Universal Windows Platform apps.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] Digital music was included until the end of 2017, and E-books were included until 2019.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] As with other similar platforms, such as the Google Play and Mac App Store, Microsoft Store is curated, and apps must be certified for compatibility and content.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] In addition to the user-facing Microsoft Store client, the store has a developer portal with which developers can interact.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] Microsoft takes 5–15% of the sale price for apps and 30% on Xbox games.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] Prior to January 1, 2015, this cut was reduced to 20% after the developer's profits reached $25,000.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] In 2021, 669,000 apps were available in the store.
