[src:winui/microsoft-store] Microsoft previously maintained a similar digital distribution system for software known as Windows Marketplace, which allowed customers to purchase software online.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] The marketplace tracked product keys and licenses, allowing users to retrieve their purchases when switching computers.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] Windows Marketplace was discontinued in November 2008.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] At this point, Microsoft opened a Web-based storefront called "Microsoft Store".
[src:winui/microsoft-store] Microsoft first announced Windows Store, a digital distribution service for Windows at its presentation during the Build developer conference on September 13, 2011.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] For consumers, Windows Store is intended to be the only way to obtain Metro-style apps.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] While announced alongside the "Developer Preview" release of Windows 8, Windows Store itself did not become available until the "Consumer Preview", released in February 2012.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] Updates to apps published on the store after July 1, 2019, are no longer available to Windows 8 RTM users.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] Per Microsoft lifecycle policies, the RTM version of Windows 8 has been unsupported since January 12, 2016, excluding some Embedded editions, as well its server equivalent, Windows Server 2012.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] An updated version of Windows Store was introduced in Windows 8.1.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] Its home page was remodeled to display apps in focused categories (such as popular, recommended, top free and paid, and special offers) with expanded details, while the ability for apps to automatically update was also added.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] Windows 8.1 Update also introduced other notable presentation changes, including increasing the top app lists to return 1000 apps instead of 100 apps, a "picks for you" section, and changing the default sorting for reviews to be by "most popular".
[src:winui/microsoft-store] Updates to apps published on the Store after June 30, 2023, are no longer available to Windows 8.1.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] Per Microsoft lifecycle policies, the Windows 8.1 Update reached the end of its extended support on January 10, 2023, excluding some Embedded editions, as well its server equivalent, Windows Server 2012 R2.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] In June 2017, Spotify became available in the Windows Store.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] In September 2017, Microsoft began to re-brand Windows Store as Microsoft Store, with a new icon carrying the Microsoft logo.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] Xbox Store was merged into this new version of the platform.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] This is in line with Microsoft's platform convergence strategy on all Windows 10-based operating systems.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] Web apps and traditional desktop software can be packaged for distribution on Windows Store.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] Desktop software distributed through Windows Store are packaged using the App-V system to allow sandboxing.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] In February 2018, Microsoft announced that Progressive Web Apps would begin to be available in the Microsoft Store, and Microsoft would automatically add selected quality progressive web apps through the Bing crawler or allow developers to submit Progressive Web Apps to the Microsoft Store.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] Starting from Windows 10 version 1803, fonts can be downloaded and installed from the Microsoft Store.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] In Windows 11, Microsoft Store received an updated user interface, and a new pop-up designed to handle installation links from websites.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] The Microsoft Store is not installed by default in Windows Server 2012 or later versions of Windows Server.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] Apps that would normally be available in the Store can be installed through sideloading.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] Microsoft Store is the primary means of distributing Universal Windows Platform (UWP) apps to users.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] Sideloading apps from outside the store is supported on Windows 10 on an opt-in basis, but Windows 8 only allows sideloading to be enabled if the device is running the Enterprise edition of Windows 8 on a domain.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] Sideloading on Windows RT, Windows 8 Pro, and on Windows 8 Enterprise computers without a domain affiliation, requires the purchase of additional licenses through volume licensing.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] Individual developers are able to register for US$19 and companies for US$99.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] Initially, Microsoft took a 30% cut of app sales until it reached US$25,000 in revenue, after which the cut dropped to 20%.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] On January 1, 2015, the reduction in cut at $25,000 was removed, and Microsoft takes a 30% cut of all app purchases, regardless of overall sales.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] As of August 1, 2021, Microsoft takes a 12% cut of app sales.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] Third-party transactions are also allowed, of which Microsoft does not take a cut.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] A range of multimedia content (music, books, movies) were formerly available on the Microsoft Store.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] They were gradually shut between 2017 to 2025, leaving only the apps & games storefront remaining.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] In 2015, over 669,000 apps were available on the store, including apps for Windows NT, Windows Phone, and UWP apps, which work on both platforms.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] Categories containing the largest number of apps are "Games", "Entertainment", "Books and Reference", and "Education".
[src:winui/microsoft-store] Both free and paid apps can be distributed through Microsoft Store, with paid apps ranging in cost from US$0.99 to $999.99.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] Developers from 120 countries can submit apps to Microsoft Store.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] Apps may support any of 109 languages, as long as they support one of 12 app certification languages.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] From 2016 to 2019, most Microsoft Studios games ported to PC were distributed exclusively via Microsoft Store.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] Microsoft later abandoned this strategy in May 2019, amid criticism of limitations faced by UWP-based games, and a desire to also sell games on competing storefronts such as Steam.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] The new Xbox app subsequently became the main frontend for PC games available via Microsoft Store, and also integrates subscription service PC Game Pass.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] On October 2, 2017, Microsoft announced that the sale of digital music on the Microsoft Store would cease on December 31 after the discontinuation of Groove Music Pass.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] Users were able to transfer their music to Spotify until January 31, 2018.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] Books bought from the Microsoft Store were formerly accessible on the EdgeHTML-based Microsoft Edge.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] The ability to open ePub e-books was removed during the shift to the Chromium-based Microsoft Edge.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] On April 2, 2019, Microsoft announced that the sale of e-books on the Microsoft Store had ceased.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] Due to DRM licenses that would not be renewed, all books became inaccessible by July 2019, and Microsoft automatically refunded all users that had purchased books via the service.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] Movies and television shows were available for purchase or rental, depending on availability.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] Content could be played on the Microsoft Movies & TV app (available for Windows 10, Xbox One, Xbox 360 and Xbox X/S), or Xbox Video app (available for Windows 8/RT PCs and tablets, and Windows Phone 8).
[src:winui/microsoft-store] In the United States, a Microsoft account can be linked to the Movies Anywhere digital locker service (separate registration required), which allows purchased content to be played on other platforms (e.g.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] Microsoft Movies & TV was available in the following 21 countries: Australia, Austria, Belgium, Brazil, Canada, Denmark, Finland, France, Germany, Ireland, Italy, Japan, Mexico, Netherlands, New Zealand, Norway, Spain, Sweden, Switzerland, the United States, and the United Kingdom.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] The purchase of TV shows was not supported in Belgium.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] On July 18, 2025, Microsoft announced the closure of its Movies & TV storefront after 12 years of operations.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] Users who live outside the US can continue to use the Movies & TV app to play previously purchased content until further notice.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] Microsoft recommended users who live in the US to use Movies Anywhere to sync their Microsoft-purchased content to other supported services such as Amazon Video or Apple TV.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] Similar to Windows Phone Store, Microsoft Store is regulated by Microsoft.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] Applicants must obtain Microsoft's approval before their app becomes available on the store.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] These apps may not contain, support or approve, gratuitous profanity, obscenity, pornography, discrimination, defamation, or politically offensive content.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] They may also not contain contents that are forbidden by or offensive to the jurisdiction, religion or norms of the target market.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] They may also not encourage, facilitate or glamorize violence, drugs, tobacco, alcohol and weapons.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] Video game console emulators that are "primarily gaming experiences or target Xbox One" and third-party web browsers that use their own layout engines, are prohibited on Microsoft Store.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] Microsoft has indicated that it can remotely disable or remove apps from end-user systems for security or legal reasons; in the case of paid apps, refunds may be issued when this is done.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] Microsoft initially banned PEGI "18"-rated content from the store in Europe.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] However, critics noted that this made the content policies stricter than intended, as some PEGI 18-rated games are rated "Mature" on the U.S.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] ESRB system, which is the next lowest before its highest rating, "Adults Only".
[src:winui/microsoft-store] The guidelines were amended in December 2012 to remove the discrepancy.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] On October 8, 2020, Microsoft announced a commitment to ten "principles" of fairness to developers in the operation of the Microsoft Store.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] The announcement came in the wake of a lawsuits against Apple, Inc. and Google LLC by Epic Games over alleged anticompetitive practices conducted by their own application stores.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] In addition to the user facing Microsoft Store client, the store also has a developer portal with which developers can interact.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] Microsoft Store provides developer tools for tracking apps in the store.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] The dashboard also presents a detailed breakdown of users by market, age, and region, as well as charts on the number of downloads, purchases, and average time spent in an app.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] Microsoft Store has widely received negative reviews since its inception.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] Unavailability of popular apps has been the leading reason for the cold reception of the store.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] Phil Spencer, head of Microsoft's gaming division, has also opined that Microsoft Store "sucks".
[src:winui/microsoft-store] As a result, Office was removed as an installable app from the store, and made to redirect to its website.
[src:winui/microsoft-store] Malware had also made its way into the store by being displayed as popular games.
[src:winui/universal-windows-platform] UWP does not target non-Microsoft systems.
[src:winui/universal-windows-platform] Microsoft's solution for other platforms is .NET MAUI (previously "Xamarin.Forms"), an open-source API created by Xamarin, a Microsoft subsidiary since 2016.
[src:winui/universal-windows-platform] Community solutions also exist for non-targeted platforms, such as Uno Platform.
[src:winui/universal-windows-platform] UWP is a part of Windows 10, Windows 10 Mobile and Windows 11.
[src:winui/universal-windows-platform] UWP apps do not run on earlier Windows versions.
[src:winui/universal-windows-platform] Apps that are capable of implementing this platform are natively developed using Visual Studio 2015, Visual Studio 2017, Visual Studio 2019, or Visual Studio 2022.
[src:winui/universal-windows-platform] Older Metro-style apps for Windows 8.1, Windows Phone 8.1, or for both (universal 8.1) need modifications to migrate to UWP.
[src:winui/universal-windows-platform] Some Windows platform features in later versions have been exclusive to UWP and software specifically packaged for it, and are not usable in other architectures such as the existing WinAPI, WPF, and Windows Forms.
[src:winui/universal-windows-platform] However, as of 2019, Microsoft has taken steps to increase the parity between these application platforms and make UWP features usable inside non-UWP software.
[src:winui/universal-windows-platform] Microsoft introduced XAML Islands (a method for embedding UWP controls and widgets into non-UWP software) as part of the Windows 10 May 2019 update, and stated that it would also allow UWP functions and Windows Runtime components to be invoked within non-packaged software.
[src:winui/universal-windows-platform] UWP Bridges translate calls in other application programming interfaces (APIs) to the UWP interface, so that applications written in these APIs would run on UWP.
[src:winui/universal-windows-platform] Two bridges are announced during the 2015 Build keynote for Android and iOS apps to be ported to Windows 10 Mobile.
[src:winui/universal-windows-platform] Until January 2022, Microsoft maintained support for bridges for Windows desktop apps, progressive web apps, Microsoft Silverlight, and iOS's Cocoa Touch API.
[src:winui/universal-windows-platform] This "WinObjC" project is open source on GitHub.
[src:winui/universal-windows-platform] It contains code from various existing implementations of Cocoa Touch like Cocotron and GNUstep as well as Microsoft's own code that implements iOS frameworks using UWP methods.
[src:winui/universal-windows-platform] It uses a version of the LLVM clang compiler.
[src:winui/universal-windows-platform] In February 2016, Microsoft announced that it had ceased development on Windows Bridge for Android, citing redundancies due to iOS already being a primary platform for multi-platform development, and that Windows Bridge for iOS produced native code and did not require an OS-level emulator.
[src:winui/universal-windows-platform] Instead, Microsoft encouraged the use of C# for multi-platform app development using tools from Xamarin, which they had acquired prior to the announcement.
[src:winui/universal-windows-platform] In 2021, Microsoft allowed Windows 11 to run Android apps with an OS-level emulator and allowed apps to be installed in the store.
[src:winui/universal-windows-platform] UWP provides an application model based upon its CoreApplication class and the Windows Runtime (WinRT).
[src:winui/universal-windows-platform] Universal Windows apps that are created using the UWP no longer indicate having been written for a specific OS in their manifest build; instead, they target one or more device families, such as a PC, smartphone, tablet, or Xbox One, using Universal Windows Platform Bridges.
[src:winui/universal-windows-platform] These extensions allow the app to automatically utilize the capabilities that are available to the particular device it is currently running on.
[src:winui/universal-windows-platform] A universal app may run on either a mobile phone or a tablet and provide suitable experiences on each.
[src:winui/universal-windows-platform] A universal app running on a smartphone may start behaving the way it would if it were running on a PC when the phone is connected to a desktop computer or a suitable docking station.
[src:winui/universal-windows-platform] Games developed for UWP are subject to technical restrictions, including incompatibility with multi-video card setups, difficulties modding the game, overlays for gameplay-oriented chat clients, or key binding managers.
[src:winui/universal-windows-platform] UWP will only support DirectX 11.1 or later, so games built on older DirectX versions will not work.
[src:winui/universal-windows-platform] Epic Games founder Tim Sweeney criticized UWP for being a walled garden, since by default UWP software may only be published and installed via Windows Store, requiring changes in system settings to enable the installation of external software (similarly to Android).
[src:winui/universal-windows-platform] Additionally, certain operating system features are exclusive to UWP and cannot be used in non-UWP software such as most video games.
[src:winui/universal-windows-platform] As such, Sweeney argued that end-users should be able to download UWP software and install it in the same manner as non-UWP software.
[src:winui/universal-windows-platform] Windows VP Kevin Gallo addressed Sweeney's concerns, stating that "in the Windows 10 November Update, we enabled people to easily side-load apps by default, with no UX required.
[src:winui/universal-windows-platform] We want to make Windows the best development platform regardless of technologies used, and offer tools to help developers with existing code bases of HTML/JavaScript, .NET and Win32, C++ and Objective-C bring their code to Windows, and integrate UWP capabilities.
[src:winui/universal-windows-platform] In a live interview with *Giant Bomb* during its E3 2016 coverage, Spencer defended the mixed reception of its UWP-exclusive releases, stating that "they all haven't gone swimmingly.
[src:winui/universal-windows-platform] Some of them have gone well", and that "there's still definitely concern that UWP and our store are somehow linked in a way that is nefarious.
[src:winui/universal-windows-platform] The end result is better for gamers." Spencer also stated that he was a friend of Sweeney and had been in frequent contact with him.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] WinRT is not a runtime in a traditional sense but rather a language-independent application binary interface based on COM to allow object-oriented APIs to be consumed from multiple languages, with services usually provided by a full-blown runtime, such as type activation.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] That is, WinRT is an "API delivery system".
[src:winui/windows-runtime] Apps using the Windows Runtime may run inside a sandboxed environment to allow greater security and stability and can natively support both x86 and ARM.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] WinRT components are designed with interoperability among multiple languages and APIs in mind, including native, managed and scripting languages.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] Built-in APIs provided by Windows which use the WinRT ABI are commonly known as WinRT APIs; however, anyone can use the WinRT ABI for their own APIs.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] WinRT is implemented in the programming language C++ and is object-oriented by design.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] Its underlying technology, the Windows API (Win32 API), is written mostly in the language C.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] It is an unmanaged application binary interface based on Component Object Model (COM) that allows interfacing from multiple languages, as does COM.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] However, the API definitions are stored in `.winmd` files, which are encoded in ECMA 335 metadata format, which .NET Framework also uses with a few modifications.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] For WinRT components implemented in native code, the metadata file only contains the definition of methods, classes, interfaces and enumerations and the implementation is provided in a separate DLL.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] This common metadata format makes it easier to consume WinRT APIs from .NET apps with simpler syntax than P/Invoke.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] Windows provides a set of built-in APIs which are built on the WinRT ABI which provide everything from the XAML-based WinUI library and device access such as camera, microphone, etc.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] The Component Extensions of C++/CX are recommended for use at the API-boundary only, not for other purposes.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] Regular C++ (with COM-specific discipline) can also be used to program with WinRT components, with the help of the Windows Runtime C++ Template Library (WRL), which is similar in purpose to what Active Template Library provides for COM.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] In 2019, Microsoft deprecated C++/CX in favor of the C++/WinRT header library.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] Most WinRT applications run within a sandbox and need explicit user approval to access critical OS features and underlying hardware.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] By default, file access is restricted to several predetermined locations, such as the directories Documents or Pictures.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] WinRT applications are packaged in the .appx and later the .msix file format; based upon Open Packaging Conventions, it uses a ZIP format with added XML files.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] WinRT applications are distributed mostly through an application store named Microsoft Store, where Windows apps (termed *Windows Store apps*) can be purchased and downloaded by users.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] Initially, WinRT apps could only be sideloaded from outside Windows Store on Windows 8 or RT systems that are part of a Windows domain, or equipped with a special activation key obtained from Microsoft.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] However these restrictions were lifted in the Windows 10 November Update, where users can freely sideload any app signed with a trusted certificate by enabling a setting.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] In a major departure from Win32 and similarly to .NET Framework 4.5, most APIs which are expected to take significant time to complete are implemented as asynchronous.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] When calling a Windows Runtime asynchronous function, the task is started on another thread or process and the function returns immediately, freeing the app to perform other tasks while waiting for results.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] The asynchronous model requires new programming language constructs.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] Each language provides their own way to consume asynchronous APIs.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] Parts of the built-in API needing asynchronous access include on-screen messages and dialogs, file access, Internet connectivity, sockets, streams, devices and services, and calendar, contacts and appointments.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] The metadata describes the APIs written using the WinRT ABI.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] It defines a programming model that makes it possible to write object-oriented code that can be shared across programming languages, and enables services like reflective programming (reflection).
[src:winui/windows-runtime] Herb Sutter, C++ expert at Microsoft, explained during his session on C++ at the 2011 Build conference that the WinRT metadata is in the same format as CLI metadata.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] Native code (i.e., processor-specific machine code) cannot contain metadata, so it is stored in a separate metadata file that can be reflected like ordinary CLI assemblies.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] Since it is the same format as CLI metadata, WinRT APIs can be used from managed CLI languages as if it was just a .NET API.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] WinRT has a rich object-oriented class-based type system that is built on the metadata.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] It supports constructs with corresponding constructs in the .NET framework: classes, methods, properties, delegates, and events.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] One of the major additions to WinRT relative to COM is the cross-application binary interface (ABI), .NET-style generics.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] Only interfaces and delegates can be generic, runtime classes and methods in them can't.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] Generic interfaces are also known as parameterized interfaces.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] In C++/CX, they are declared using the keyword `generic` with a syntax very similar to that of keyword `template`.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] WinRT classes (ref classes) can also be genericized using C++ templates, but only template instantiations can be exported to .winmd metadata (with some name mangling), unlike WinRT generics which preserve their genericity in the metadata.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] WinRT also provides a set of interfaces for generic containers that parallel those in the C++ Standard Library, and languages provide some reciprocal (back-and-forth) conversion functions.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] The consumption of WinRT collections in .NET languages (e.g., C# and VB) and in JavaScript is more transparent than in C++, with automated mappings into their natural equivalents occurring behind the scenes.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] When authoring a WinRT component in a managed language, some extra, COM-style rules must be followed, e.g. .NET framework collection types cannot be declared as return types, but only the WinRT interfaces that they implement can be used at the component boundary.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] Classes that are compiled to target the WinRT are called *WinRT components*.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] They are classes that can be written in any supported language and for any supported platform.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] This metadata makes it possible to interface with the component from any other WinRT language.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] The runtime requires WinRT components that are built with .NET Framework to use the defined interface types or .NET type interfaces, which automatically map to the first named.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] Inheritance is as yet not supported in managed WinRT components, except for XAML classes.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] Programs and libraries targeted for the WinRT runtime can be created and consumed from several platforms and programming languages.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] Notably C/C++ (either with language extensions offering first-class support for WinRT concepts, or with a lower-level template library allowing to write code in standard C++), .NET (C# and Visual Basic (.NET) (VB.NET)) and JavaScript.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] Standard C++ is a *first-class citizen* of the WinRT platform.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] As of Windows 10, version 1803, the Windows SDK contains C++/WinRT.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] C++/WinRT is an entirely standard modern C++17 language projection for Windows Runtime (WinRT) APIs, implemented as a header-file-based library, and designed to provide first-class access to the modern Windows API.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] With C++/WinRT, Windows Runtime APIs can be authored and consumed using any standards-compliant C++17 compiler.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] WinRT is a native platform and supports any native (and standard) C++ code, so that a C++ developer can reuse existing native C/C++ libraries.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] With C++/WinRT, there are no language extensions.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] There are two other legacy options for using WinRT from C++: Windows Runtime C++ Template Library (WRL), an ATL-style template library (similar to Windows Template Library or WTL), and C++/CX (C++ with Component Extensions) which resembles C++/CLI.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] Because of the internal consumption requirements at Microsoft, WRL is exception-free, meaning its return-value discipline is HRESULT-based just like that of COM.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] C++/CX on the other hand wraps-up calls to WinRT with code that does error checking and throws exceptions as appropriate.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] C++/CX has several extensions that enable integration with the platform and its type system.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] The syntax resembles the one of C++/CLI although it produces native (although not standard) code and metadata that integrates with the runtime.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] For example, WinRT objects may be allocated with `ref new`, which is the counterpart of `gcnew` from C++/CLI.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] The hat operator `^` retains its meaning, however in the case where both the caller and callee are written in C++ and living in the same process, a hat reference is simply a pointer to a vptr to a virtual method table (vtable, VMT).
[src:winui/windows-runtime] Along with C++/CX, relative to traditional C++ COM programming, are partial classes, again inspired by .NET.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] These allow instance WinRT XAML code to be translated into C++ code by tools, and then combined with human-written code to produce the complete class while allowing clean separation of the machine-generated and human-edited parts of a class implementation into different files.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] The .NET Framework and the Common Language Runtime (CLR) are integrated into the WinRT as a subplatform.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] It has influenced and set the standards for the ecosystem through the metadata format and libraries.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] The CLR provides services like JIT-compilation code and garbage collection.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] WinRT applications using .NET languages use the XAML-based WinUI, and are primarily written in C#, VB.NET, and for the first time for XAML, with native code using C++/CX.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] Although not yet officially supported, programs can also be written in other .NET languages.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] With .NET 5, Microsoft removed the built-in WinRT support and instead created CsWinRT, a tool that generates interop code for accessing Windows Runtime APIs similar to how C++/WinRT works.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] Classes defined in WinRT components that are built in managed .NET languages must be declared as `sealed`, so they cannot be derived from.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] However, non-sealed WinRT classes defined elsewhere can be inherited from in .NET, their virtual methods overridden, and so on; but the inherited managed class must still be sealed.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] Members that interface with another language must have a signature with WinRT types or a managed type that is convertible to these.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] WinRT applications can also be coded using HTML with JavaScript in code-behind, which are run using the Trident rendering engine and Chakra JavaScript engine, both of which are also used by Internet Explorer.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] When coding a WinRT app in JavaScript, its features are adapted to follow JavaScript naming conventions, and namespaces are also mapped to JavaScript objects.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] Microsoft is in the process of projecting WinRT APIs to languages other than C++.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] One example is Rust/WinRT, an interface for programs written in Rust to consume and author WinRT APIs.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] Rust/WinRT is part of Windows App SDK (formerly Project Reunion), a Microsoft effort to reconcile traditional Windows desktop and the UWP app model.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] With the introduction of the Universal Windows Platform (UWP), the platform has received many API bridges that allow programs originally developed for other platforms to be ported easily while taking advantage of UWP features.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] Microsoft has provided bridges for Android (defunct since 2016), iOS (Cocoa Touch), Progressive Web Apps, Silverlight, as well as traditional Windows desktop apps (using MSIX packaging from the Windows App SDK).
[src:winui/windows-runtime] WinRT comes with an application programming interface (API) in the form of a class library that exposes the features of Windows 8 for the developer, like its immersive interface API.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] It is accessible and consumable from any supported language.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] The Windows Runtime classes is a set SDKs that provide access to all functionality from the XAML parser to the camera function.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] The SDKs are implemented as native C/C++ libraries (unmanaged).
[src:winui/windows-runtime] The naming conventions for the components (classes and other members) in the API are heavily influenced by the .NET naming conventions which uses camel case (specifically PascalCase).
[src:winui/windows-runtime] Microsoft recommends users to follow these rules in case where no others are given.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] These conventions are projected differently in some languages, like JavaScript, which converts it to its conventions and the other way around.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] This is to give a native and consistent experience regardless of the programming language.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] Since Windows Runtime is projected to various languages, some restrictions on fundamental data types exist so as to host all such languages.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] Programmers must be careful with the behavior of those types when used with public access (for method parameters, method return values, properties, etc.).
[src:winui/windows-runtime] In .NET languages and C++, a rich set of data types exists, representing various numerals.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] can only represent up to 53 bits of precision.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] In WinRT, the only lacking numeral data type is 8-bit signed integer relative to .NET and C++.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] JavaScript developers must be careful when dealing with big numbers while coding for WinRT.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] Strings are immutable in .NET and JavaScript, but mutable in C++.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] In .NET and C++, structs are value types, and such a struct can contain any type in it.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] JavaScript does not directly support structs.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] In WinRT, use of structs is allowed only for containing types that have value semantics, including numerals, strings, and other structs.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] Pointers or interface references are disallowed.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] In .NET, objects are passed by reference, whereas numerals and structs are passed by value.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] In C++, all types can be passed by reference or value.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] In WinRT, interfaces are passed by reference; all other types can be passed either by value or by reference.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] In .NET, C++, and JavaScript arrays are reference types.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] In WinRT, arrays are value types and quite restricted.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] property is used to subscribe to events.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] In WinRT, all languages can use their own way to subscribe to events.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] Some .NET collections map directly to WinRT collections.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] type resembles arrays and the array syntax is used to consume them.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] type is a key/value pair collection, and is projected as Dictionary in .NET languages.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] .NET and C++ also support overloading on type.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] In WinRT, only parameter number is used for overloading.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] All WinRT methods are designed such that any method taking longer than 50 milliseconds is an async method.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] For the full runtime library, all methods that have a chance to last longer than 50 ms are implemented as asynchronous methods only.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] Windows Phone 8.1 uses a version of the Windows Runtime named the *Windows Phone Runtime*.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] It enables developing applications in C# and VB.NET, and Windows Runtime components in C++/CX.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] Although WP8 brought limited support, the platform did eventually converge with Windows 8.1 in Windows Phone 8.1.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] Windows Phone 8 has limited support for developing and consuming Windows Runtime components through *Windows Phone Runtime*.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] Many of the Windows Runtime APIs in Windows 8 that handle core operating system functions have been ported to Windows Phone 8.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] Support for developing native games using C++/CX and DirectX has been added, by request from the game development industry.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] However, the Windows Phone XAML Framework is still based on the same Microsoft Silverlight framework, as in Windows Phone 7, for backward compatibility.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] Thus, as of 2016, XAML development is impossible in C++/CX.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] Development using either HTML5 or WinJS is unsupported on Windows Phone 8.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] Windows Runtime support on Windows Phone 8.1 converges with Windows 8.1.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] The release brings a full Windows Runtime API to the platform, including support for WinRT XAML, and language bindings for C++/CX, and HTML5-JavaScript.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] There is also a project type called *Universal apps* to enable apps to share code across 8.1 versions of Windows Phone and Windows.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] The Windows Phone 8 Silverlight Framework has been updated.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] It can exploit some of the new features in the Windows Runtime.
[src:winui/windows-runtime] Windows Phone Runtime uses the AppX package format from Windows 8, after formerly using Silverlight XAP.
[src:winui/winui] WinUI is one of the multiple UI frameworks provided built-in for the Windows Runtime; the others being HTML5 (e.g., via WinJS) and DirectX.
[src:winui/winui] WinUI 2 is an extension library for UWP XAML containing controls and styling that match the Windows 11 design language.
[src:winui/winui] It is shipped through NuGet and is distinct from the UWP XAML framework, which provides the actual rendering engine; though, they may be treated as synonyms.
[src:winui/winui] WinUI 3 decouples WinRT XAML from the operating system as a separate package to be updated quickly and make new features work on older versions of Windows.
[src:winui/winui] It is part of Windows App SDK (codenamed "Project Reunion"), a Microsoft effort to reconcile the Windows desktop (Win32) and the UWP low IL app model.
[src:winui/winui] Up to Windows Phone 8.0 WinRT XAML was not supported and XAML applications were based on Silverlight XAML and deployed in XAP format.
[src:winui/winui] In Windows Phone 8.1 WinRT XAML is available along with improved Windows Runtime support.
[src:winui/winui] This convergence between platforms enable Universal apps that can target both Windows 8.1 and Windows Phone 8.1 while sharing most of the code, including user interface.
[src:winui/winui] WinUI is related to Windows Presentation Foundation (WPF) and Silverlight (WPF/E)—similar XAML-based UI frameworks used for desktop applications and portable applications respectively.
[src:winui/winui] WinUI uses a lot of the same names for its APIs as both of these older technologies—especially Silverlight, but its use is limited to the Windows (specifically Windows 8 and later) as with WPF.
[src:winui/winui] The major difference is that WPF and Silverlight are written in C# and require using .NET languages such as C# or Visual Basic, while WinRT XAML is part of the Windows Runtime, written in C++ and available to native code, and has tools for development, with C++/CX or C++/WinRT.
